text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeArticle:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingComment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!PracticeCategory]]%0a%0a!Is Shakespeare Even English?%0a%0a:Author: aryans%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHow much does a language have to change to not be considered the same language anymore?%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aAs a high school student in the United States, I had to read my fair share of Shakespeare. We used editions which gave the original Shakespeare on the right page and the translation into plain English on the opposing left page. I also took Mandarin Chinese in high school, and I noticed that the organizational structure in the Shakespeare editions was extremely similar to that of passages in my Chinese textbook. That’s when I began to think that something was fishy about this Shakespeare business. If I had to translate it into English to understand it, it wasn’t English, was it? %0a%0aI already had a rudimentary understanding of the fact that languages change over time, and that this effect compounded over centuries can have drastic consequences. For example, Old English, the earliest form of English spoken in the latter half of the first millennium, is completely unintelligible to any ordinary speaker of modern English. Beowulf is an epic poem originally written in Old English, and all that usually sells is the modern translation without the Old English original. Here’s a block of the first three lines of the original Old English Beowulf from Poetry Foundation for reference:%0a%0aHwæt. We Gardena in geardagum, %0aþeodcyninga, þrym gefrunon, %0ahu ða æþelingas ellen fremedon. %0a%0aYeah, I got nothing from that too. I think that most people would agree that Old English is an entirely different language than the English you and I are familiar with, even if your English and my English are slightly different from each other.%0a%0aIn the same vein, there are also significant differences between the English Shakespeare used and the English we use. In fact, translations of Shakespeare into modern speech are often necessary to teach the plays effectively. I would say that this means that the language Shakespeare wrote in is not the same language that we call English. Thus formed the crux of my argument to my AP literature teacher that it was inappropriate to teach Shakespeare in a class on English literature. %0a%0aI was, of course, joking (although I did want to get out of reading Shakespeare). But I always wondered where the line was. At what point has a language changed so much that it’s no longer the same language? %0a%0aResources: %0a%0aBeowulf (Old English Version). Poetry Foundation, retrieved 1 Feb 2021, from%0a	https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/43521/beowulf-old-english-version %0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210202-122725-860540#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Maybe...?%0a- [- Mingkang_L -]%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI definitely agree that Shakespeare's language is quite different from modern English today. As a non-native speaker of English, I found it almost impossible to understand the original text at first, and learning to read Shakespeare in high school was really like learning a new language for me. However, I would say it's still quite similar to modern English compared to Middle English (e.g. The Canterbury Tales) and Old English you mentioned. It doesn't have gender or cases any more, and the verb/noun conjugation has been simplified a lot. The Great Vowel Shift was also partially complete, making it sound more similar to modern-day English, so from these characteristics I think it can still be considered English. %0aI actually had the same question when I was learning classical Chinese in high school. Texts written over 2000 years ago (Confucius and Lao Tze's time) are impossible to decipher without numerous annotations and translation, while poems written over 1000 years ago are somewhat understandable with a few footnotes, while novels written 500 years ago are actually quite accessible, but they don't have a clear demarcation from each other. Perhaps this suggests that languages evolve very slowly, and there is not a clear line between "the old" and "the new," so the best thing we can do is to point to a rough period where the major changes took place.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210202-122725-860540#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210203-092702-685390#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-03.02.2021 - 01:27-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a!!!!!Mingkang_L%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Maybe...?'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0a(Sorry I should have posted this under comments) I definitely agree that Shakespeare's language is quite different from modern English today. As a non-native speaker of English, I found it almost impossible to understand the original text at first, and learning to read Shakespeare in high school was really like learning a new language for me. However, I would say it's still quite similar to modern English compared to Middle English (e.g. The Canterbury Tales) and Old English you mentioned. It doesn't have gender or cases any more, and the verb/noun conjugation has been simplified a lot. The Great Vowel Shift was also partially complete, making it sound more similar to modern-day English, so from these characteristics I think it can still be considered English. I actually had the same question when I was learning classical Chinese in high school. Texts written over 2000 years ago (Confucius and Lao Tze's time) are impossible to decipher without numerous annotations and translation, while poems written over 1000 years ago are somewhat understandable with a few footnotes, while novels written 500 years ago are actually quite accessible, but they don't have a clear demarcation from each other. Perhaps this suggests that languages evolve very slowly, and there is not a clear line between "the old" and "the new," so the best thing we can do is to point to a rough period where the major changes took place. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210203-092702-685390#%0a#foxbegin 210203-014838-937760#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-02.02.2021 - 17:48-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a!!!!!jnflores%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Is it a dialect?'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aSomewhat influenced by other articles I saw in this category, could Shakespearean English be a dialect of modern English? I agree with the author's claim, that modern translations support the idea Shakespeare's speech is not our English, but it has to be related somehow, right?  %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210203-014838-937760#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:Section: :)%0a(:Category: PracticeCategory:)
