P literature teacher that it was inappropriate to teach Shakespeare in a class on English literature. %0a%3c I was, of course, joking (although I did want to get out of reading Shakespeare). But I always wondered where the line was. At what point has a language changed so much that it’s no longer the same language? %0a%3c Resources: %0a%3c Beowulf (Old English Version). Poetry Foundation, retrieved 1 Feb 2021, from%0a%3c 	https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/43521/beowulf-old-english-version %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a---%0a> As a high school student in the United States, I had to read my fair share of Shakespeare. We used editions which gave the original Shakespeare on the right page and the translation into plain English on the opposing left page. I also took Mandarin Chinese in high school, and I noticed that the organizational structure in the Shakespeare editions was extremely similar to that of passages in my Chinese textbook. That’s when I began to think that something was fishy about this Shakespeare business. If I had to translate it into English to understand it, it wasn’t English, was it? %0a> I already had a rudimentary understanding of the fact that languages change over time, and that this effect compounded over centuries can have drastic consequences. For example, Old English, the earliest form of English spoken in the latter half of the first millennium, is completely unintelligible to any ordinary speaker of modern English. Beowulf is an epic poem originally written in Old English, and all that usually sells is the modern translation without the Old English original. Here’s a block of the first three lines of the original Old English Beowulf from Poetry Foundation for reference:%0a> Hwæt. We Gardena in geardagum, %0a> þeodcyninga, þrym gefrunon, %0a> hu ða æþelingas ellen fremedon. %0a> %0a> Yeah, I got nothing from that too. I think that most people would agree that Old English is an entirely different language than the English you and I are familiar