dation for reference:%0a%3c Hwæt. We Gardena in geardagum, %0a%3c þeodcyninga, þrym gefrunon, %0a%3c hu ða æþelingas ellen fremedon. %0a%3c %0a%3c Yeah, I got nothing from that too. I think that most people would agree that Old English is an entirely different language than the English you and I are familiar with, even if your English and my English are slightly different from each other.%0a%3c In the same vein, there are also significant differences between the English Shakespeare used and the English we use. In fact, translations of Shakespeare into modern speech are often necessary to teach the plays effectively. I would say that this means that the language Shakespeare wrote in is not the same language that we call English. Thus formed the crux of my argument to my AP literature teacher that it was inappropriate to teach Shakespeare in a class on English literature. %0a%3c I was, of course, joking (although I did want to get out of reading Shakespeare). But I always wondered where the line was. At what point has a language changed so much that it’s no longer the same language? %0a%3c Resources: %0a%3c Beowulf (Old English Version). Poetry Foundation, retrieved 1 Feb 2021, from%0a%3c 	https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/43521/beowulf-old-english-version %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:Section: :)%0a%3c (:Category: PracticeCategory:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
